    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-04-26T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-04-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="607"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.796/321: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Vincent</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-04-27T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >April 27, 1943—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 27—10:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>607. Bond tells me that he has been approached with proposal that CNAC make
                    available a number of its pilots to “check out” (training given co-pilots until
                    they are familiar with routes and flying and landing conditions) new pilots for
                        RAF<note n="18" xml:id="d607fn18">Royal Air Force.</note> planes to be
                    operated out of Chungking, Kweilin and Lanchow. He understands that transport
                    planes will be used and surmises that British plan to make up for deficiency of
                    CNAC planes on interior Chinese routes. He has been told however that reason
                    behind contemplated RAF operation is probably political.</p>
                <p>Bond is leaving in few days for Washington. With reference to Department’s 422,
                    March 30, midnight, he says that CNAC has prospect of receiving a few additional
                    planes for its passenger service.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Vincent</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
